  "prompt": "How often do a Tesla's batteries need to be replaced?",
  "response": "Tesla batteries are designed to last a long time, typically around 300,000 to 500,000 miles, depending on the model and usage. The lifespan of a Tesla battery can be influenced by factors such as charging habits, climate, and driving patterns.\n\nMost Tesla vehicles come with an 8-year or 100,000 to 150,000-mile warranty, which covers battery performance, ensuring that the battery retains a certain percentage of its original capacity during that time. Many Tesla owners report a capacity loss of only about 5-10% over the first several years of use, which is relatively low compared to some other electric vehicles.\n\nWhile some owners may start considering battery replacement after many years or high mileage, many users find their batteries last well beyond the warranty period without the need for replacement. Regular maintenance and proper charging practices can help extend battery life.",
